lained}}\n* {{YouTube|UFhJefdVCjE|StatQuest: P-value pitfalls and power calculations}}\n\n{{-}}\n{{Statistics}}\n\n[[Category:Statistical hypothesis testing]]\n\n[[ja:\u6709\u610f#p\u5024]]\n", "name_user": "Theswampman", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eDistribution", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/P-value"}
{"title_page": "Juan Escoto", "text_new": "'''Juan Escoto''' (1894\u20131975) was a Mexican children's book author and politician. Born in [[Le\u00f3n, Guanajuato]] on January 16, 1894.  Escoto completed his studies in his native land of [[Guanajuato]]. He was the author of multiple children's books and an anthology of poetry related to his childhood. He served in several posts in the state government of Guanajuato, including minister of culture. In 1972 he help found the first international [[Festival internacional cervantino]], dedicated to celebrating the works of [[Miguel de Cervantes]]. The festival has grown into a major annual festival of theater and culture held in the city of [[Guanajuato, Guanajuato]].\n\n==Selected works==\n*\"Mas vale p\u00e1jaro en mano (historias inocentes)\" - 1928\n*\"Las curvas de Tapachula y otros cuentos\" - 1942\n*\"El Quijote de Teotihuacan y otros ensayos Cervantinos\" - 1960\n*\"El Lloyd Escoto filibusterismo\" - 1966\n\n==Sources==\n* Juan L\u00f3pez de Escalera, ''Diccionario biogr\u00e1fico y de historia de M\u00e9xico''. Editorial Magisterio, M\u00e9xico, 1964.\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Escoto, Juan}}\n[[Category:20th-century Mexican writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century Mexican male writers]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Guanajuato]]\n[[Category:Writers from Guanajuato]]\n[[Category:People from Le\u00f3n, Guanajuato]]\n[[Category:1894 births]]\n[[Category:1975 deaths]]\n[[Category:State political office-holders in Mexico]]\n\n\n{{Mexico-writer-stub}}\n{{Mexico-politician-stub}}\n", "text_old": "'''Juan Escoto''' (1894\u20131975) was a Mexican children's book author and politician. Born in [[Le\u00f3n, Guanajuato]] on January 16, 1894.  Escoto completed his studies in his native land of [[Guanajuato]]. He was the author of multiple children's books and an anthology of poetry related to his childhood. He served in several posts in the state government of Guanajuato, including minister of culture. In 1972 he help found the first international [[Festival internacional cervantino]], dedicated to celebrating the works of [[Miguel de Cervantes]]. The festival has grown into a major annual festival of theater and culture held in the city of [[Guanajuato, Guanajuato]].\n\n==Selected works==\n*\"Mas vale p\u00e1jaro en mano (historias inocentes)\" - 1928\n*\"Las curvas de Tapachula y otros cuentos\" - 1942\n*\"El Quijote de Teotihuacan y otros ensayos Cervantinos\" - 1960\n*\"El Lloyd Escoto filibusterismo\" - 1966\n\n==Sources==\n* Juan L\u00f3pez de Escalera, ''Diccionario biogr\u00e1fico y de historia de M\u00e9xico''. Editorial Magisterio, M\u00e9xico, 1964.\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Escoto, Juan}}\n[[Category:20th-century Mexican writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century Mexican male writers]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Guanajuato]]\n[[Category:Writers from Guanajuato]]\n[[Category:People from Le\u00f3n, Guanajuato]]\n[[Category:1894 births]]\n[[Category:1975 deaths]]\n[[Category:State political office-holders in Mexico]]\n\n\n{{Mexico-writer-stub}}\n{{Mexico-politician-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSources:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Juan_Escoto"}
{"title_page": "The Balkan Line", "text_new": "{{Infobox film\n| name     = The Balkan Line\n| image    = The Balkan Line.jpg\n| caption  = Movie poster\n| director = [[Andrey Volgin (film director)|Andrey Volgin]] \n| producer = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Gosha Kutsenko]]\n* Vadim Byrkin \n* Vasil Sevc \n* Tatyana Kuranova \n* Anastasiya Pelevina\n* Dmitriy Rubezhin\n* Dmitriy Zemskov\n* [[Milo\u0161 Bikovi\u0107]]\n* Miodrag Radonji\u0107\n}}\n| writer = {{Plainlist|\n* Ivan Naumov \n* Natalya Nazarova \t\n* Andrey Anaykin \n}}\n| starring = {{Plainlist|\n* Anton Pampushnyy\n* [[Gosha Kutsenko]]\n* [[Milo\u0161 Bikovi\u0107]]\n* [[Gojko Miti\u0107]]\n* [[Ravshana Kurkova]]\n}}\n| music          = \n| cinematography = \n| editing        = \n| studio         = Upgrade Vision <br> Bless Film <br> Archangel Studios\n| distributor    = [[20th Century Fox]] [[Commonwealth of Independent States|CIS]]\n| released       = {{Film date|2019|03|21|df=yes}}\n| runtime        = 130 minutes\n| country        = [[Russia]], [[Serbia]]\n| language       = [[Russian language|Russian]], [[Serbian language|Serbian]]\n| budget         = {{Russian ruble}}230{{nbsp}}million ({{US$|3.6 million|long=no}})<ref>{{cite news |title=\u0413\u043e\u0448\u0430 \u041a\u0443\u0446\u0435\u043d\u043a\u043e 15 \u0441\u0435\u043d\u0442\u044f\u0431\u0440\u044f \u043d\u0430\u0447\u043d\u0435\u0442 \u0441\u043d\u0438\u043c\u0430\u0442\u044c\u0441\u044f \u043d\u0430 \u0411\u0430\u043b\u043a\u0430\u043d\u0430\u0445 \u0432 \u043d\u043e\u0432\u043e\u043c \u0444\u0438\u043b\u044c\u043c\u0435 |url=https://tass.ru/kultura/4491914 |accessdate=17 June 2019 |work=\u0422\u0410\u0421\u0421 |agency=[[TASS]] |date=18 August 2017}}</ref>\n| gross          = {{US$|5.85 million|long=no}}<ref>{{cite web |title=The Balkan Line |url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/intl/?id=_fTHEBALKANLINE01 |website=[[Box Office Mojo]] |accessdate=22 May 2019}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''The Balkan Line''''' ({{lang-ru|\u0411\u0430\u043b\u043a\u0430\u043d\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u0440\u0443\u0431\u0435\u0436|Balkanskiy rubezh}}; {{lang-sr|{{lang|sr-Cyrl|\u0411\u0430\u043b\u043a\u0430\u043d\u0441\u043a\u0430 \u043c\u0435\u0452\u0430}} / {{lang|sr-Latn|Balkanska me\u0111a}}}}) is a 2019 [[Russia]]n\u2013[[Serbia]]n [[Action film|action film]] directed by Andrey Volgin,<ref>[https://gorod24.online/crimea/news/88104-sikvelyi_bayopiki_ekranizatsii_bestsellerov_samyie_ojidaemyie_filmyi_2019go.html \u0421\u0438\u043a\u0432\u0435\u043b\u044b, \u0431\u0430\u0439\u043e\u043f\u0438\u043a\u0438, \u044d\u043a\u0440\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0437\u0430\u0446\u0438\u0438 \u0431\u0435\u0441\u0442\u0441\u0435\u043b\u043b\u0435\u0440\u043e\u0432: \u0441\u0430\u043c\u044b\u0435 \u043e\u0436\u0438\u0434\u0430\u0435\u043c\u044b\u0435 \u0444\u0438\u043b\u044c\u043c\u044b 2019 \u0433\u043e\u0434\u0430]</ref><ref>[https://ria.ru/20190110/1549153466.html  \u00ab\u0421\u043f\u0430\u0441\u0442\u0438 \u041b\u0435\u043d\u0438\u043d\u0433\u0440\u0430\u0434\u00bb  \u0438  \u00ab\u0417\u0432\u0451\u0437\u0434\u043d\u044b\u0435 \u0432\u043e\u0439\u043d\u044b\u00bb: \u0441\u0430\u043c\u044b\u0435 \u043e\u0436\u0438\u0434\u0430\u0435\u043c\u044b\u0435 \u0444\u0438\u043b\u044c\u043c\u044b 2019 \u0433\u043e\u0434\u0430]</ref><ref>[https://vz.ru/culture/2019/1/2/957768.html \u0421\u0430\u043c\u044b\u0435 \u043e\u0436\u0438\u0434\u0430\u0435\u043c\u044b\u0435 \u0444\u0438\u043b\u044c\u043c\u044b 2019 \u0433\u043e\u0434\u0430]</ref> dedicated to the [[Incident at Pristina airport|secret operation]] to capture the [[Slatina Airport]] in [[Kosovo]] after the [[NATO bombing of Yugoslavia]]. These events became the most dangerous aggravation of relations between the Russian Federation and the West since the [[Cuban Missile Crisis]].\n\nThe film was released in Russia on 21 March 2019, three days prior to the 20th anniversary of the bombing of Yugoslavia. It was released by [[20th Century Fox]] [[Commonwealth of Independent States|CIS]].\n\n== Plot ==\nThe film takes place in 1999 during the [[NATO bombing of Yugoslavia|bombing]] of [[Republic of Serbia (1992\u20132006)|Serbia]] and [[Republic of Montenegro (1992\u20132006)|Montenegro]] (the two [[constituent state|constituent republics]] comprising the [[Serbia and Montenegro|Federal Republic of Yugoslavia]]). Slatina airfield is controlled by terrorists led by an Albanian warlord, Smuk. The film shows the operation to capture the airfield, which is conducted by [[Russian intelligence]] officers.<ref>[https://www.kinoafisha.info/movies/8327057/ \u0411\u0430\u043b\u043a\u0430\u043d\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u0440\u0443\u0431\u0435\u0436, 2018]</ref> Removal of human organs takes place within the territories terrorists have taken, as do robberies, mass assassinations and genocide. \n\nRussian intelligence officer Aslan-Bek Evkhoev and former paratrooper turned mercenary Andrey Shatalov head a small detachment tasked with the dangerous mission to stop the terrorism, recapture the airfield used by the terrorists and rescue Shatalov's love interest Jasna Blagojevi\u0107, who was captured to be [[War crimes in the Kosovo War#Organ theft|harvested for organs]], like the rest of the Serbian prisoners.\n\n== Cast ==\n* {{ill|Anton Pampushnyy|fr|Anton Pampouchny}} as Andrey Shatalov \"Shatay\"<ref>[http://portal-kultura.ru/articles/cinema/225687-anons-2019/ \u0410\u043d\u043e\u043d\u0441-2019]</ref> \n* [[Gosha Kutsenko]] as Aslan-Bek \"Bek\" Evkhoev (based on [[Yunus-bek Yevkurov]])\n* [[Milo\u0161 Bikovi\u0107]] as Vuk Majevski, Yugoslav police officer\n* {{ill|Milena Radulovi\u0107|sr|\u041c\u0438\u043b\u0435\u043d\u0430 \u0420\u0430\u0434\u0443\u043b\u043e\u0432\u0438\u045b}} as Jasna Blagojevi\u0107, doctor\n* [[Gojko Miti\u0107]] as Goran Mili\u0107, head of the Serbian police station\n* Sergey Marin as Ilya Slashchev \"Slush\"\n* Nodari Janelidze as Rustam Mamatgireyev \"Girey\"\n* [[Kirill Polukhin]] as Oleg Barmin \"Baria\", sapper\n* [[Ravshana Kurkova]] as Vera Kurbaeva, sniper\n* Dmitriy Frid as Dr. Stern, doctor from [[Switzerland]], Smuk's accomplice\n* {{ill|Aleksandar Sre\u0107kovi\u0107 (actor)|sr|\u0410\u043b\u0435\u043a\u0441\u0430\u043d\u0434\u0430\u0440 \u0421\u0440\u0435\u045b\u043a\u043e\u0432\u0438\u045b|lt=Aleksandar Sre\u0107kovi\u0107}} as Smuk \n* {{ill|Svetlana Chuykina|ru|\u0427\u0443\u0439\u043a\u0438\u043d\u0430, \u0421\u0432\u0435\u0442\u043b\u0430\u043d\u0430 \u0412\u043b\u0430\u0434\u0438\u043c\u0438\u0440\u043e\u0432\u043d\u0430}} as Marta, doctor, assistant to Dr. Stern\n* {{ill|Miodrag Radonji\u0107|sr|\u041c\u0438\u043e\u0434\u0440\u0430\u0433 \u0420\u0430\u0434\u043e\u045a\u0438\u045b}} as Amir \n* Nikola Randelovi\u0107 as Stevan \n* Roman Kurtsyn as Senior Lieutenant Nikolay Poltoratskiy, platoon commander\n* [[Emir Kusturica]] as taxi driver (cameo appearance)\n* Mikhail Khmurov as General Somov<ref>[https://www.imdb.com/title/tt5951188/fullcredits?ref_=tt_cl_sm#cast \u0411\u0430\u043b\u043a\u0430\u043d\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u0440\u0443\u0431\u0435\u0436 (2019) Full Cast & Crew]</ref>\n\n== Production ==\nThe main role was played by [[Gosha Kutsenko]], who is also listed as a producer.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://en.film.ru/news/konflikt-v-kosovo|title=Gosha Kutsenko in the second trailer of the film ''The Balkan Line''|work=Film.ru}}</ref>\n\n== Release ==\nThe film was released to Russia, Serbia, Kyrgyzstan, Armenia, Belarus and Kazakhstan on March 21, 2019.\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{IMDb title|id=5951188}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Balkan Line, The}}\n[[Category:2019 films]]\n[[Category:Russian films]]\n[[Category:2010s action films]]\n[[Category:Russian-language films]]\n[[Category:Serbian-language films]]\n[[Category:Russian action films]]\n[[Category:Serbian action films]]\n[[Category:2010s multilingual films]]\n[[Category:2010s action thriller films]]\n[[Category:2010s war films]]\n[[Category:Russian action thriller films]]\n[[Category:Action war films]]\n[[Category:Russian war films]]\n[[Category:Serbian war films]]\n[[Category:Yugoslav Wars films]]\n[[Category:Films set in 1995]]\n[[Category:Bosnian War films]]\n[[Category:Period action films]]\n[[Category:Films set in 1999]]\n[[Category:Action films based on actual events]]\n[[Category:Pregnancy films]]\n[[Category:Films set in Kosovo]]\n[[Category:Films set in Belgrade]]\n[[Category:Russian multilingual films]]\n[[Category:Films about terrorism in Europe]]\n[[Category:Russian films about revenge]]\n[[Category:Films about mass murder]]\n[[Category:Historical epic films]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Moscow]]\n[[Category:Films set in Moscow]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Serbia]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Crimea]]\n[[Category:Films set in Serbia]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox film\n| name     = The Balkan Line\n| image    = The Balkan Line.jpg\n| caption  = Movie poster\n| director = [[Andrey Volgin (film director)|Andrey Volgin]] \n| producer = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Gosha Kutsenko]]\n* Vadim Byrkin \n* Vasil Sevc \n* Tatyana Kuranova \n* Anastasiya Pelevina\n* Dmitriy Rubezhin\n* Dmitriy Zemskov\n* [[Milo\u0161 Bikovi\u0107]]\n* Miodrag Radonji\u0107\n}}\n| writer = {{Plainlist|\n* Ivan Naumov \n* Natalya Nazarova \t\n* Andrey Anaykin \n}}\n| starring = {{Plainlist|\n* Anton Pampushnyy\n* [[Gosha Kutsenko]]\n* [[Milo\u0161 Bikovi\u0107]]\n* [[Gojko Miti\u0107]]\n* [[Ravshana Kurkova]]\n}}\n| music          = \n| cinematography = \n| editing        = \n| studio         = Upgrade Vision <br> Bless Film <br> Archangel Studios\n| distributor    = [[20th Century Fox]] [[Commonwealth of Independent States|CIS]]\n| released       = {{Film date|2019|03|21|df=yes}}\n| runtime        = 130 minutes\n| country        = [[Russia]], [[Serbia]]\n| language       = [[Russian language|Russian]], [[Serbian language|Serbian]]\n| budget         = {{Russian ruble}}230{{nbsp}}million ({{US$|3.6 million|long=no}})<ref>{{cite news |title=\u0413\u043e\u0448\u0430 \u041a\u0443\u0446\u0435\u043d\u043a\u043e 15 \u044