lection|1965]]\n| party17a = Liberal\n| seats17a = 2\n| party17c = Social Credit\n| seats17c = 3\n| party17b = Progressive Conservatives\n| seats17b = 1\n| year18 = [[1963 Canadian federal election|1963]]\n| party18a = Liberal\n| seats18a = 1\n| party18b = Social Credit\n| seats18b = 5\n| year19 = [[1962 Canadian federal election|1962]]\n| party19a = Social Credit\n| seats19a = 6\n| year20 = [[1958 Canadian federal election|1958]]\n| party20a = Liberal\n| seats20a = 1\n| party20b = Progressive Conservatives\n| seats20b = 5\n| year21 = [[1957 Canadian federal election|1957]]\n| party21a = Liberal\n| seats21a = 6\n| year22 = [[1953 Canadian federal election|1953]]\n| party22a = Liberal\n| seats22a = 4\n| party22b = Independent \n| seats22b = 2\n}}\n\n'''Canadian federal elections''' have provided the following '''results''' in '''the C\u00f4te-Nord and Saguenay'''.\n\n==Regional Profile==\nThis region used to be traditionally [[Liberal Party of Canada|Liberal]], except for Roberval which has voted for the Social Credit Party. The Liberal dominance ended in [[1984 Canadian federal election|1984]] as [[Brian Mulroney]], who is from this area, was able to gather Quebec nationalist support and sweep the region in 1984 and [[1988 Canadian federal election|1988]]. With the advent of the nationalist [[Bloc Qu\u00e9b\u00e9cois]] in 1993, nationalist support left the Tories, and this area became a traditional Bloc stronghold. This is true except for the [[Chicoutimi, Quebec|Chicoutimi]] area which has voted federalist with [[Andr\u00e9 Harvey]] running as a [[Progressive Conservative Party of Canada|Progressive Conservative]] and winning in 1997, and running as a [[Liberal Party of Canada|Liberal]] and winning in 2000. The Bloc swept the region in 2004, but the [[Conservative Party of Canada|Conservatives]] picked up a seat here in [[2006 Canadian federal election|2006]] and weakened the Bloc's grip on the remaining seats as Liberal support collapsed. In 2011, another regional sweep gave four of the five seats to the [[New Democratic Party of Canada|New Democrats]], shutting out the Bloc and leaving the Conservatives with one of their two seats. In the 2015 election, the NDP lost all but one of its seat in the region, while the Bloc managed a comeback in the C\u00f4te-Nord region, the Liberals won one seat in Chicoutimi and the Conservatives won one seat in the southwestern part of the region near Quebec City.\n\n=== Votes by party throughout time ===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+Evolution of party standings throughout time\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" colspan=\"2\" scope=\"col\"|Party\n! colspan=\"2\"  scope=\"col\"|1984\n! colspan=\"2\"  scope=\"col\"|1988\n! colspan=\"2\"  scope=\"col\"|1993\n! colspan=\"2\"  scope=\"col\"|1997\n! colspan=\"2\"  scope=\"col\"|2000\n! colspan=\"2\"  scope=\"col\"|2004\n! colspan=\"2\"  scope=\"col\"|2006\n! colspan=\"2\"  scope=\"col\"|2008\n! colspan=\"2\"  scope=\"col\"|2011\n! colspan=\"2\"  scope=\"col\"|2015\n! colspan=\"2\"  scope=\"col\"|2019\n|-\n!scope=\"col\"|Votes\n!scope=\"col\"|%\n!scope=\"col\"|Votes\n!scope=\"col\"|%\n!scope=\"col\"|Votes\n!scope=\"col\"|%\n!scope=\"col\"|Votes\n!scope=\"col\"|%\n!scope=\"col\"|Votes\n!scope=\"col\"|%\n!scope=\"col\"|Votes\n!scope=\"col\"|%\n!scope=\"col\"|Votes\n!scope=\"col\"|%\n!scope=\"col\"|Votes\n!scope=\"col\"|%\n!scope=\"col\"|Votes\n!scope=\"col\"|%\n!scope=\"col\"|Votes\n!scope=\"col\"|%\n!scope=\"col\"|Votes\n!scope=\"col\"|%\n|-\n| {{Canadian party colour|CA|Liberal|background}}|\n| |{{Canadian party colour|CA|Liberal|name}}\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"|78,279\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"|32.7%\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"|48,609\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"|17.9%\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"|41,916\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"|15.5%\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"|59,370\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"|23.3%\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"|85,687\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"|35.5%\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"|57,501\n| style=\"te